> crypto happens in both sbot and in the ui

elaborating a little to foster understanding: the sbot server uses the same kind of crypto to authenticate local client connections that it uses for remote peers, so that it can whiteliste api calls when you are connecting to yourself with your own key. That way authentication is based on secret key file access and you don't have to use localhost ip whitelisting which could be fatal on a multi user system or accidental listening on `*:8080`.

I was bummbed by this when writing our golang port since I only wanted access to my local db but aftewards was very happy that it also enabled my code to speak to remote peers.

> do we want new users to follow pubs? 

Technically it is possible to onboard people without pub invites. It’s just not simple of you are not in the same room/doing it async. If i and the new uxer both Post `contact:` Messages to follow each other she can connect to pubs and other peers without ever using an invite. Our friendship will be enough for pubs (granted, with hop > 0) to accept her connection and sync.

I think the iffy part her is the async setting since you can’t follow them until they made a key.

> Is that essentially clicking the "follow" button? 

to make it short: yes. `type:contact` is used for following and blocking. I think patchbay only shows `type:post` in the feed and annotates votes/digs on them. ( patchbay and -foo have a nerdier approach towards messages. They show all the messages but it can feel spammy at times since you see all the dig/follow/subscribe sprees that people go through. )

> do you mean the real life setting of not being in the same room, or on at the same time?

yup, that is exactly what I meant and you are correct on all counts. You could add your own public key to your generated personal invite, which is also much safer because e2e encryption is nothing without some proper key verification but it's also just a matter of time before there are more than one _zach_ here.. ;)

buuut if I'd have to run an errand suddenly and couldn't _let the new person in_ for a few hours that would be a pretty bad onboarding experience in my book but it is perfect for the sync setting and it is what we should strive for imho since it also maps much better onto the personal friend-of-a-friend thing.

# 5 common UX dark patterns and user-friendly alternatives

> .. dark patterns stop working after a while and companies have to think of something else

> > “Any short-term gains a company gets from a dark pattern are lost in the long term,”

I think this is a crucial point to realize. If you use such tricks, even through neglect, it can drive people away from your platform.

## 1 Deliberate Misdirection
> Users are directed to buy travel insurance, but on clicking the dropdown menu they see a list of Countries of Residence. The opt-out for purchasing travel insurance is way down the list, under the unintuitive listing ‘No travel insurance required’.
> You think you’re picking travel insurance, but then suddenly you’re telling them your country of residence, and it doesn’t look like deselecting travel insurance is an option.

Sinister and thus not that much of a trap for us, I think.

## 2 Invisible Unsubscribe
> Invisible unsubscribes are the worst cases of dark UX. But plenty of reputable companies try to make it difficult. Take Amazon, who grays out their Unsubscribe option. Or companies who format it to make it look like it doesn’t have a link.

Also pretty deliberate. I also think we are aware of the dangers that lie in notifcations (inbox spam/pollution) and will watch out to pick sensible defaults and communicate how to controll them.

## 3 Growth Hacking Through Spamming
> This can happen when apps or services you join ask for access to your email contacts — they make out like they just want to help you find friends already using the same service, but in reality they want to spam all your contacts with invitations to join up.

Not happening on my watch. Not interested in mindlessly slurping up contact data or directly briding in people from other platforms.

## 4 Forced Continuity

means enrolling users _for free_ but actually giving them trial access to premium features, coercing them to upgrade when the trial runs out eventually.

Not a problem for use since this won't be a paid service.

## 5 Expanding Shopping Basket

Also not a problem for use since we won't sell anything.

# Dark Patterns: The Sinister Side of UX

## Forced continuity

already covered above. It is commonly more about automatically extending free trials into payed ones, still not a problem for our case.

## Misdirection

also already covered but adds a good example involving the use of colors in the interface.

> Players are trained to associate the green buttons with gameplay. You select a green button to start the game once you’ve opened the app. Then once again when you’ve selected the level you’d like to play, and yet again before you begin that level. That’s three times you’re asked to select the green button.
> Now here’s what players see if they lose a round:

Yup.. a green _buy more moves_ button. The author says she lost count of how many times she clicked on it by accident and I can sympathize also because I played the same game.

I think this could happen by accident, using the default button color in a place that actually needs more attention. If the user is in the mood to advance to the next screen you shouldn't use the color that the user is trained to use to advance.

Also good points for improvement (even if you aren't making software that sells stuff:

> * Give all options equal weight – While you may really want your users to click that buy button, you don’t want them to feel tricked into doing so. Present choices as equally as possible so that your users don’t feel misled.
> * Confirm – If you don’t have the space to put all the options on the table, then make sure you’re confirming after a selection is made by your user. Reiterate back to your user what they’ve just selected, and give them the option to continue or cancel.

## Roach motel

> The concept is simple: make it easy for users to “get in,” and then make it exceedingly difficult to “get out.”

# [EFAIL](https://efail.de) describes vulnerabilities in the end-to-end encryption technologies OpenPGP and S/MIME that leak the plaintext of encrypted emails.


> Mitigations
> Here are some strategies to prevent EFAIL attacks:

> Short term: No decryption in email client. The best way to prevent EFAIL attacks is to only decrypt S/MIME or PGP emails in a separate application outside of your email client. Start by removing your S/MIME and PGP private keys from your email client, then decrypt incoming encrypted emails by copy&pasting the ciphertext into a separate application that does the decryption for you. That way, the email clients cannot open exfiltration channels. This is currently the safest option with the downside that the process gets more involved.

> Short term: Disable HTML rendering. The EFAIL attacks abuse active content, mostly in the form of HTML images, styles, etc. Disabling the presentation of incoming HTML emails in your email client will close the most prominent way of attacking EFAIL. Note that there are other possible backchannels in email clients which are not related to HTML but these are more difficult to exploit.

> Medium term: Patching. Some vendors will publish patches that either fix the EFAIL vulnerabilities or make them much harder to exploit.

> Long term: Update OpenPGP and S/MIME standards. The EFAIL attacks exploit flaws and undefined behavior in the MIME, S/MIME, and OpenPGP standards. Therefore, the standards need to be updated, which will take some time.

# Direct Anonymous Attestation (DAA)

from [wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Direct_Anonymous_Attestation):

> DAA is a cryptographic primitive which enables remote authentication of a trusted computer whilst preserving privacy of the platform's user. The protocol has been adopted by the Trusted Computing Group (TCG) in the latest version of its Trusted Platform Module (TPM) specification ...
> # Overview
> The DAA protocol is based on three entities and two different steps. The entities are the DAA Member (TPM platform or EPID-enabled microprocessor), the DAA Issuer and the DAA Verifier. The issuer is charged to verify the TPM platform during the Join step and to issue DAA credential to the platform. The platform (Member) uses the DAA credential with the Verifier during the Sign step. Through a zero-knowledge proof the Verifier can verify the credential without attempting to violate the platform's privacy. The protocol also supports a blacklisting capability so that Verifiers can identify attestations from TPMs that have been compromised.
> # Privacy properties
> The protocol allows differing degrees of privacy. Interactions are always anonymous, but the Member/Verifier may negotiate as to whether the Verifier is able to link transactions. This would allow user profiling and/or the rejection of requests originating from a host which has made too many requests. The Member and Verifier can also elect to reveal additional information to accomplish non-anonymous interactions (just as you can choose to tell a stranger your full name, or not). Thus, known identity can be built on top of an anonymous start. (Contrast this with: if you start with known identity, you can never prove you un-know that identity to regress to anonymity.)
